<div class="jumbotron">
    <h1>Emotion Log</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        Have you ever struggled to care enough to get out of bed in the morning?  Have you gone through your days in a mental
        fugue, lost to the world without desire to come back?  Can you remember how long it’s been since you’ve been happy?
        For many, these questions are real and relevant somewhat regularly, yet the world is so colored by the experience that
        they feel that the way they feel at any given moment is they way they’ve always felt.  Trapped within their own heads,
        there is a sense of powerlessness to change things on the bad days and denial that things need changed on the good days.
        Time loses all meaning.
    </p>
    <p>
        This is where Emotion Log comes in.  It is a starter step, a way to see the ebb and flow of your own emotional state.
        Just log in once a day (or more!) and answer a few questions about how your day is going and we’ll help you track how
        you’re doing.  (Initial – visual pain scale for how are you feeling) (Outside the scope of this project – greater range
        of questions to track other life factors that may be impacting things such as remembering to eat, drink, hours of sleep,
        what did you do today – user defined answers, etc.)
    </p>
</div>

<div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-4">
        <h2>Eating Right</h2>
        <p>
            Many factors in our mood are indirect.  Diet is incredibly important, both in knowing what we're putting into
            our bodies as well as how often we eat.  Depression often has the side effect of less healthy dietary habits
            through the lack of emotional energy to encourage good eating habits.  Depression can lead to eating too much
            or too little, and frequently the wrong thing.  We are drawn to comfort foods instead of healthy foods, we
            gravitate to quickly prepared foods instead of things that take more effort.
        </p>
        <p><a class="btn btn-default" href="https://sustainabledish.com/eat-meat-beat-depression/">Protien matters &raquo;</a></p>
    </div>
